Bingham miners’
hit deportations

BINGHAM CANYON, Utah-—-Mem-

‘ bership of Bingham Open Pit, Miners’

Union, Local 485, are‘ aroused over the
arrest for deportation of 31 members
in recent weeks. , /.

They have all been picked up under
terms of the McCarran-Walter Act
which went into effect late in 1952.
Several of them have won as much as
two and three years’ seniority on the
job in Bingham Canyon.

Mine-Mill members are not the only
ones being arrested. The'Immigration
Department has picked up hundreds of
others during their current drive in
Utah and Idaho. -

Nachio Ortego, Local 485 financial
secretary, and Int’l rep. D. B. Bay-
liff, were told by the Mexican consul
in Salt Lake City that the basis for the
deportation arrests is the charge of
violation of contracts which the Mexi-
can workers signed before entering the
U. S. , —

The contracts, with such companies
as Del Monte Canning Co. and Utah-
Idaho Sugar Co., call for the Mexican
worker to come to the ‘U. S. to work
in back-breaking agricultural jobs at
wages -no higher than 65 or 75 cents an
hour. The‘ workers are obligedto live
in shacks provided by the big contrac-
tors, for which they pay $2 or $3 “rent”
and board a day. , _

None‘ of the contracts have limits on
hours ‘or provisions for overtime or
grievance machinery. They are given
the blessing of the U. S. Department of
labor every year. The workers are sup-

'pose<i_ to go back to Mexico as soon as
the “season” is over. , ,

Local 485, at its last‘ membership
meeting, voted to write letters of pro-
test against the “contract system” to
both the U. S. Department of Labor
and the Mexican-Department of Labor.
They also voted to move into action for
repeal of the McCarran-Walter Act,
which led to the latest drive against
the Mexican nationals.

 

